english:
  title: On the Ruined Earth Chamber
  author: Lee Gyeo-bo
  language: eng
  text: On the first day of the tenth month, Lee returned from his travels to find his sons had dug into the earth and built a chamber, its shape resembling a tomb. Feigning ignorance, Lee asked, "Why have you constructed a grave within our home?" The sons replied, "This is not a grave, Father—it is an earth chamber." "But for what purpose?" he demanded. "In winter, it preserves flowers and fruits," they explained. "And for the women who spin and weave, even in the harshest cold, it remains warm as spring itself. Their hands do not crack and bleed from frost. Is this not wonderful?" Lee's anger deepened. "Summer's heat and winter's cold follow the natural order of the seasons. To reverse this is to invite calamity. The ancient sages established clothing—furs for winter, hemp for summer—and such provisions are sufficient. Yet you build this earth chamber to turn cold into warmth, defying Heaven's decree. We are neither serpents nor toads to hibernate in burrows through the winter—nothing brings greater misfortune. And spinning has its proper season. Why must it be done in winter? Moreover, the blooming of spring and withering of winter are the natural way of plants. To reverse this is to violate the nature of things. To cultivate such violations as unseasonable amusements is to usurp Heaven's authority. None of this accords with my will. If you do not tear this down at once, I shall beat you without mercy." Terrified, the sons hastily dismantled the chamber. They used its materials for firewood. Only then did Lee's heart find peace.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The earth chamber (土室) was an underground storage structure used in medieval Korea to maintain stable temperatures for preserving produce and providing warm workspaces during harsh winters.
  - key: ''
    value: This piece exemplifies Lee Gyeo-bo's characteristic style of philosophical discourse through dramatic narrative, addressing the tension between human artifice and natural order.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "sages of old" (古聖人) invokes Confucian ideals of harmony with natural seasons and established propriety.
